Reflection & Learning Portfolio

🧠 What I Built & Learned

During this assignment, I worked on multiple IoT-based projects using the ESP32 microcontroller and simulation tools like Wokwi. 
These projects were focused on solving real-world problems using sensors, automation, and data communication.

One of the key projects I built was the Smart Greenhouse Controller. 
In this system, I monitored temperature and humidity using a DHT sensor and light intensity using an LDR. 
Based on predefined ranges (Temperature: 18–22°C, Humidity: 60–70%), I implemented control logic to simulate a heater, fan, and grow light using LEDs. 
I also used averaging techniques to stabilize sensor readings. This project helped me understand how IoT is used in agriculture for maintaining optimal crop conditions.

Another important project was the River Water Level Alert System. 
I used an ultrasonic sensor (HC-SR04) to measure water levels and classify them into three categories: NORMAL (>30 cm), WARNING (15–30 cm), and CRITICAL (<15 cm). 
The system triggered LEDs and buzzer alerts with different patterns for each level. I also implemented a rolling average to reduce noise in sensor readings and worked with wireless communication and dashboards. 
This project showed how IoT can be applied in disaster management and early warning systems.

I also developed a Heart Rate & SpO₂ Monitoring System (Simulation) using an LDR as a proxy sensor. 
The system generated simulated readings, applied a rolling average to smooth them, and displayed values on the serial monitor. 
Alerts were triggered when heart rate was below 50 bpm or above 120 bpm, or when SpO₂ dropped below 94%. 
This helped me understand how health monitoring systems process and react to real-time data.

Through these projects, I learned several important IoT concepts:

Interfacing sensors with microcontrollers
Handling noisy data using rolling averages
Implementing threshold-based and control logic
Debugging both hardware and code issues
Using Wokwi for simulation and testing

